{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 11:31:16.359114", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary\n- Symptom: Client cannot reach the web service at http://web0.pod0 (10.0.1.2:80). DNS resolution works, ICMP pings to 10.0.1.2 succeed, but TCP connections are refused.\n- Key finding: The leaf router for the webserver’s subnet (leaf_router_0_1) is incorrectly configured with a loopback address 10.0.1.0/25 that overlaps the service subnet 10.0.1.0/24. This causes the leaf to “own” 10.0.1.2 and respond to traffic locally, preventing forwarding to the actual webserver.\n- Fault localization: leaf_router_0_1.\n- Root cause: Overlapping/incorrect IP assignment on leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.0/25 on lo), leading to interception of traffic destined to 10.0.1.0/25 (including 10.0.1.2) and TCP RST responses.\n\nEvidence and Findings\n\nEnd-to-end reachability and application tests\n- DNS resolution from client_0:\n  - getent hosts web0.pod0 returns 10.0.1.2 (OK).\n  - /etc/resolv.conf contains nameserver 10.0.0.2; named on dns_pod0 is active.\n- HTTP from client_0:\n  - curl http://web0.pod0 and http://10.0.1.2 return code:000; curl -v shows “Connection refused”.\n  - nc -vz 10.0.1.2 80 from client_0 fails (rc:1).\n- Ping from client_0 to 10.0.1.2 succeeds (0% loss). This is misleading (see below).\n- On webserver0_pod0:\n  - Service is listening: python3 -m http.server 80 (LISTEN on 0.0.0.0:80).\n  - Local testing succeeds: curl http://127.0.0.1 and http://10.0.1.2 return HTTP 200.\n  - No host firewall blocking: iptables/nftables accept; only Docker DNS NAT rules.\n\nPacket path observations\n- On super_spine_router_0 during client connect attempt:\n  - Observed SYN from 192.168.0.2:54130 to 10.0.1.2:80 followed immediately by RST-ACK from 10.0.1.2:80 to 192.168.0.2:54130.\n- On webserver0_pod0 during the same attempts:\n  - No TCP 80 traffic observed on eth0 (tcpdump empty). The SYN never reached the server.\n- On leaf_router_0_1:\n  - ICMP ping from client to 10.0.1.2 shows the leaf sending ICMP echo replies “Out IP 10.0.1.2 > 192.168.0.2”, indicating the leaf is responding as if it owns 10.0.1.2.\n\nLeaf router configuration anomaly (leaf_router_0_1)\n- IP addressing:\n  - eth2: 10.0.1.1/24 (expected for the service subnet).\n  - lo: 10.0.1.0/25 scope global (unexpected, overlapping the service subnet).\n- Routing/ARP:\n  - Kernel route includes connected 10.0.1.0/24 on eth2 (OK).\n  - ARP entry exists for 10.0.1.2 with host MAC, but traffic is not forwarded to eth2 because 10.0.1.2 is within the locally assigned 10.0.1.0/25 on loopback.\n  - Result: The kernel treats 10.0.1.2 as a local address and delivers packets to the local stack instead of forwarding to the L2 segment. It then:\n    - Responds to ICMP echo as 10.0.1.2 (making pings look healthy).\n    - Sends TCP RST for connections to 10.0.1.2:80 (no process bound on that IP:port on the router), causing “Connection refused” from the client’s perspective.\n\nFabric control-plane status (BGP)\n- All EBGP sessions across super-spine/spines/leaves are established and exchanging prefixes as expected.\n- The leaf is advertising the service subnet upstream; control plane appears healthy and not the cause of the application failure.\n\nImpact assessment\n- All hosts in the lower half of the service subnet (10.0.1.0/25), including webserver0_pod0 at 10.0.1.2, are effectively hijacked by leaf_router_0_1’s loopback assignment. External clients cannot establish TCP sessions to these hosts; pings may falsely appear healthy due to the leaf answering.\n- Hosts in 10.0.1.128/25 might not be impacted.\n\nDiagnosis\n- Anomaly detected: Yes — TCP connectivity to the web server is broken while ICMP and DNS appear normal.\n- Faulty device: leaf_router_0_1.\n- Root cause: Erroneous local IP configuration on leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.0/25 assigned to loopback), overlapping the service subnet and causing the leaf to intercept and locally terminate traffic to 10.0.1.2 (RST to TCP, ICMP reply spoofed), preventing the traffic from reaching webserver0_pod0.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11645, "output_tokens": 4382, "total_tokens": 16027, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11136}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3200}}}
